VIII. 1 This important question occurs, whether punishment may always be exacted for tho delicts of the general body. So long as the constitution of the body continues, it would seem that it can, because the same body remains, though preserved by a succession of different particles, as we have elsewhere shewn. But, on the con- trary side, it is to be observed that some things are asserted of the body primarily and per se, as to have a treasury, laws, and the 1ike3 others only derivatively from its members. Thus we call a body learned and bravo, which has many learned and bravo members. And desert [of punishment, G.] is of this kind; for, in the first place, it belongs to individuals, as having a spirit and intelligenee which the body by itself has not. Therefore if these persons be extinct, from whom desert was deduced and carried to the account of the body, the desert is extinct, and also the desert of punishment3 which, as we have said, cannot exist without desert.
